SUMMARY:'Media Effects & Mental Health: Changing the Conversation' publi
 c forum
DESCRIPTION:The forum will feature:&#160\;Michael Rich\, director of the 
 Digital Wellness Lab at Boston Children's Hospital\, associate professor 
 of pediatrics at Harvard Medical School\, and founder of Center on Intera
 ctive Media and Internet Disorders  David Bickham\, research director of 
 the Digital Wellness Lab at Boston Children's Hospital\, assistant profes
 sor of pediatrics at Harvard Medical School and Harvard T.H. School of Pu
 blic Health    The discussion centers on distinguishing nuanced\, yet inf
 luential portrayals of mental health from common clichés\, and on how st
 orytelling and movie techniques can better capture complexity\, context\,
  and lived experience.  Additional guests from IU include:&#160\;Natasha 
 Chaku\, Department of Psychological and Brain Sciences  Novotny Lawrence 
 (https://mediaschool.indiana.edu/people/profile.html?p=wnlawren)\, direct
 or of the Black Film Center &amp\; Archive\, The Media School  Lorenzo Lo
 renzo-Luaces\, Department of Psychological and Brain Sciences  Bernice A.
  Pescosolido\, Department of Sociology and director of the Irsay Institut
 e  Kaiwen Sun\, Luddy School of Informatics\, Computing\, and Engineering
 &#160\;  Paul Wright (https://mediaschool.indiana.edu/people/profile.html
 ?p=paulwrig)\, The Media School    We ultimately aim to identify concrete
  steps to shift how mental health is represented\, understood\, and addre
 ssed in contemporary media ecosystems.
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p>  The forum will feature:&#160\;</p><ul><
 li>Michael Rich\, director of the Digital Wellness Lab at Boston Children
 's Hospital\, associate professor of pediatrics at Harvard Medical School
 \, and founder of Center on Interactive Media and Internet Disorders  </l
 i><li>David Bickham\, research director of the Digital Wellness Lab at Bo
 ston Children's Hospital\, assistant professor of pediatrics at Harvard M
 edical School and Harvard T.H. School of Public Health  </li></ul><p>  Th
 e discussion centers on distinguishing nuanced\, yet influential portraya
 ls of mental health from common clichés\, and on how storytelling and mo
 vie techniques can better capture complexity\, context\, and lived experi
 ence.</p><p>  Additional guests from IU include:&#160\;</p><ul><li>Natash
 a Chaku\, Department of Psychological and Brain Sciences  </li><li><a hre
 f="https://mediaschool.indiana.edu/people/profile.html?p=wnlawren" target
 ="_blank" rel="noopener">Novotny Lawrence</a>\, director of the Black Fil
 m Center &amp\; Archive\, The Media School  </li><li>Lorenzo Lorenzo-Luac
 es\, Department of Psychological and Brain Sciences  </li><li>Bernice A. 
 Pescosolido\, Department of Sociology and director of the Irsay Institute
   </li><li>Kaiwen Sun\, Luddy School of Informatics\, Computing\, and Eng
 ineering&#160\;  </li><li><a href="https://mediaschool.indiana.edu/people
 /profile.html?p=paulwrig" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Paul Wright</a>\
 , The Media School  </li></ul><p>  We ultimately aim to identify concrete
  steps to shift how mental health is represented\, understood\, and addre
 ssed in contemporary media ecosystems.</p>
